{{Infobox company | name = Wevorce | logo = | type = | industry = Legal | fate = | predecessor = <!-- or: | predecessors = --> | successor = <!-- or: | successors = --> | founded = 2012 | founder = Michell Crosby | defunct = <!-- {{End date|YYYY|MM|DD}} --> | hq_location_city = Boise, Idaho | hq_location_country = | area_served = <!-- or: | areas_served = --> | key_people = | products = | owner = <!-- or: | owners = --> | num_employees = | num_employees_year = <!-- Year of num_employees data (if known) --> | parent = | website = {{URL|https://www.wevorce.com/}} }}
'''Wevorce''' is an American mediation [[legal technology]] company specializing in amicable [[divorce]].
Wevorce was co-founded by former attorney, Michelle Crosby, and marketing executive, Jeff Reynolds,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blog.ycombinator.com/founder-stories-michelle-crosby-wevorce-yc-w13|title=Founder Stories: Michelle Crosby, Wevorce (YC W13)|website=blog.ycombinator.com|publisher=Y Combinator}}</ref> in 2012. The company was founded in [[Boise, Idaho]], and relocated to the [[San Francisco Bay Area]] when it was selected to participate in [[Y Combinator (company)|Y Combinator]], a Mountain View, California-based startup accelerator.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.businessinsider.com/wevorce-raises-3-million-from-techstars-2016-1|title=There's a startup that will help you get divorced super fast, and it just raised $3 million|work=Business Insider|access-date=2018-08-13}}</ref> It returned to Boise in 2013 to build the company.<ref name="autogenerated1">{{cite web|last=Rich|first=Nathaniel|title=Silicon Valley's Start-Up Machine|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2013/05/05/magazine/y-combinator-silicon-valleys-start-up-machine.html?pagewanted=all&_r=0|publisher=New York Times}}</ref> The company has raised $1.7 million in venture capital funding.<ref>{{cite web|last=Taylor|first=Colleen|title=Wevorce Gets $1.7 Million To Use Technology To Make Divorce Less Messy|url=https://techcrunch.com/2013/11/21/wevorce-funding/|publisher=Tech Crunch}}</ref>
== Platform == Wevorce uses [[alternative dispute resolution]] techniques combined with its own 5-step methodology<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wevorce.com|title=Wevorce Homepage}}</ref> and technology.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/meghancasserly/2013/04/10/wevorce-y-combinator-technology-divorce-court/|title=Can This Y Combinator Startup's Technology Keep Couples Out of Divorce Court?|last=Casserly|first=Meghan|publisher=Forbes|accessdate=20 August 2013}}</ref> The company's technology reduce's the cost of divorce to between $1,800 to $10,000, about one-third the national average of a typical divorce.<ref name="ABC News">{{cite web|url=http://abcnews.go.com/blogs/lifestyle/2014/07/new-website-wevorce-eases-grueling-divorce-process/|title=New Website 'Wevorce' Eases Grueling Divorce Process|publisher=ABC News|accessdate=23 July 2014}}</ref>
